http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this update:
[1] Syria (Deir Al Zour): suspected, WHO
[2] Global update: Polio Eradication Initiative

******
[1] Syria (Deir Al Zour): suspected, WHO
Date: Sat 19 Oct 2013
Source: WHO Global Alert and Response (GAR), Disease Outbreak News [edited]
http://www.who.int/csr/don/don_updates/en/index.html


Report of suspected polio cases in the Syrian Arab Republic - [19 Oct 2013]
----------------------------------------------------------------------
On [17 Oct 2013], the World Health Organization (WHO) received reports of a cluster of acute flaccid paralysis (AFP) cases in the Syrian Arab Republic. This cluster of 'hot' AFP was detected in early October 2013 in Deir Al Zour province and is currently being investigated. Initial results from the national polio laboratory in Damascus indicate that 2 of the cases could be positive for polio -- final results are awaited from the regional reference laboratory of the Eastern Mediterranean Region of WHO. Wild poliovirus was last reported in Syria in 1999.

The Ministry of Health of the Syrian Arab Republic confirms that it is treating this event as a cluster of 'hot' AFP cases, pending final laboratory confirmation, and an urgent response is currently being planned across the country. Syria is considered at high-risk for polio and other vaccine-preventable diseases due to the current situation.

A surveillance alert has been issued for the region to actively search for additional potential cases. Supplementary immunization activities in neighbouring countries are currently being planned.

WHO's International Travel and Health recommends that all travelers to and from polio-infected areas be fully vaccinated against polio.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Marianne Hopp

[As mentioned in the report above, if confirmed, these will be the 1st cases of polio confirmed in Syria since 1999. According to a newswire report on this event, a cluster of "10 paralysis cases" has been identified in Syria (see Helen Branswell's article in the Canadian Press at http://globalnews.ca/news/912945/polio-suspected-in-war-torn-syria-who-says-potential-exists-for-large-outbreak/). Still pending is confirmation that a poliovirus has been identified from one or more of these AFP cases, and if so, what type of poliovirus (wild poliovirus -- WPV -- vs possible vaccine derived poliovirus -- VDPV). And, if WPV is identified, the genetic profile of the virus to determine the possible origin of the virus. WPV genetically related to WPV in Pakistan has been circulating in nearby Israel and the West Bank and the Gaza Strip. Additional information of interest is the age of the cases and their vaccination histories.

Unfortunately it appears as though civil unrest is a significant factor impeding the polio eradication efforts. The disruption of the public health infrastructures in countries with civil unrest, combined with security concerns where vaccinators have been targets for violence, is a major obstacle.

The province (governorate) of Deir al Zour (Dayr az Zawr) can be seen on the map at http://www.ephotopix.com/syria_province_map.html. It is located in the northeast of the country, bordering with Iraq. If WPV is confirmed, given the civil unrest in Iraq, one wonders if there might be WPV circulating across the border in Iraq as well.

For the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Syria, see http://healthmap.org/r/8S1u. - Mod.MPP]

******
[2] Global update: Polio Eradication Initiative
Date: Wed 16 Oct 2013
Source: Global Polio Eradication Initiative [edited]
http://polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek.aspx


Global Polio Eradication Initiative update as of 16 Oct 2013
------------------------------------------------------------
Wild poliovirus (WPV) cases
Total cases: Year-to-date 2013 / Year-to-date 2012 / Total 2012
Globally: 296 / 171 / 223
- in endemic countries: 99 / 166 / 217
- in non-endemic countries: 197 / 5 / 6

